'''Henry C. Boren''' (February 10, 1921 in [[Pike County, IL]] - October 17, 2013 in [[Pittsboro, North Carolina]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Henry Boren  Obituary|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/newsobserver/obituary.aspx?n=henry-boren&pid=167677459|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The News & Observer|date=24 October 2013}}</ref>  was a historian and author.  He was professor emeritus of history at the University of North Carolina.

==Professional life==
Boren is an author of numerous professional articles and books on [[ancient history]] specializing in [[ancient Rome]], including "[[Roman History|Roman Society]], A [[Social History|Social]], [[Economic History|Economic]] and [[Cultural History]]."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/633288122.html?dids=633288122:633288122&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+01%2C+1965&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Review+1+--+No+Title&pqatl=google|title=(Review, title missing)|quote=The Roman Republic by Henry C BorenAnvil Original $1.45 A delightful readable history of Rome from its legendary beginnings to the ...|date=Aug 1, 1965|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=L3|accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref><ref name="WilsonMakowski1990">{{cite book|last1=Wilson|first1=Katharina M.|last2=Makowski|first2=Elizabeth M.|title=Wykked wyves and the woes of marriage: misogamous literature from Juvenal to Chaucer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VSGTK74Q6rMC&pg=PA173|accessdate=6 April 2011|year=1990|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-0062-3|page=173}}</ref><ref name="BentleyZiegler2006">{{cite book|last1=Bentley|first1=Jerry H.|last2=Ziegler|first2=Herbert F.|title=Traditions & Encounters: From the beginning to 1500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SP-_mEMxvPgC|accessdate=6 April 2011|year=2006|publisher=McGraw Hill|isbn=978-0-07-299827-6|page=284}}</ref>

