'''Luis de Ávila y Zúñiga''' (c. 1490 &ndash; c. 1560) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[historian]].

==Life==
Born in [[Placentia, Italy|Placentia]], Ávila y Zúñiga came to the attention of the [[List of Spanish monarchs|king of Spain]], the [[Holy Roman Empire|Holy Roman Emperor]] [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]], serving him as [[ambassador]] to [[Rome]]. He was made a grand commander of the order of the [[Knights of Alcantara]] and accompanied the emperor to [[Africa]] in 1541. He also participated with Charles in the [[Schmalkaldic War|war]] against the [[Schmalkaldic League]], culminating in the [[Battle of Mühlberg]] on 24 April 1547. {{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

After the defeat of the Schmalkaldic League, Ávila y Zúñiga wrote a history of the war entitled ''Commentarios de la guerra de Alemania, hecha de Carlos V en el año de 1546 y 1547'' (''Commentaries on the war in Germany under Charles V in the years 1546 and 1547''). The book, first published in [[1548 in literature|1548]], was very popular in its time, and was translated into [[French language|French]], [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[German language|German]], [[Italian language|Italian]], and [[Latin language|Latin]]. Many have since criticized the accuracy of the account, which is very partial to the author's patron, Emperor Charles V.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

