'''Sarah Gristwood''' is an English journalist and author.<ref name="Harper">{{cite web|title=Sarah Gristwood|url=https://www.harpercollins.co.uk/cr-102120/sarah-gristwood|publisher=HarperCollins|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref> She was born in [[Kent]] and educated at [[St Anne's College, Oxford]].<ref name="Harper"/>

As a journalist she has written for a number of British papers, including [[The Times]], [[The Guardian]] and the [[Telegraph Media Group|Telegraph]].<ref name="Huffpost">{{cite web|title=Sarah Gristwood|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/sarah-gristwood/|access-date=16 February 2018}}</ref> She has written historical biographies as well as fiction, and has contributed to television documentaries.<ref name="Huffpost"/>

Gristwood's historical biography, ''Arbella: England's Lost Queen'' is about [[Lady Arbella Stuart]], an English noblewoman who was considered a possible successor to [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]]. In a review in The Times, Kevin Sharpe wrote, "Sarah Gristwood presents a powerful story of the dynastic insecurity of the Tudors and Stuarts, and of the vulnerability of Elizabeth and James to foreign and domestic intrigues."<ref name="Sharpe">{{cite newspaper|title=Review: Biography: Arbella, England's Lost Queen by Sarah Gristwood|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/review-biography-arbella-englands-lost-queen-by-sarah-gristwood-8bd3lvzjkcc|author=Sharpe, Kevin|date=2 February 2003|publisher=The Sunday times|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref>

Her book, ''Game of Queens: The Women Who Made Sixteenth-Century Europe'', focuses on five queens: [[Catherine de Medici]], [[Anne Boleyn]], [[Mary I of England]], Elizabeth I, and [[Mary, Queen of Scots]].<ref name="Dunant">{{cite newspaper|title=Women of Thrones|author=Dunant, Sarah|author-link=Sarah Dunant|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/02/books/review/game-of-queens-sarah-gristwood.html|publisher=New York Times|date=2 December 2016|accessdate=16 February 2008}}</ref> 

She has appeared in the movie ''[[Venice/Venice]]'' (1992), and as herself in the television series ''Stars of the Silver Screen'' (2011) and ''Discovering Fashion: The Designers'' (2015).<ref name="imbd">{{cite web|title=Sarah Gristwood|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0318100/?ref_=nmbio_bio_nm|website=IMDb|accessdate=17 February 2018}}</ref>

Gristwood is married to the historian and film critic, [[Derek Malcolm]].<ref name"Derek">{{cite newspaper|title=Skeletons in the Closet|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/skeletons-in-the-closet-7222148.html|date=6 March 2003|publisher=Evening Standard|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref> 

