The '''Senbonza theater''' was a theater in [[Kyoto, Japan]] in the late 19th Century. Actor [[Onoe Matsunosuke]] worked there near the start of his career in 1889,<ref name="Modern" /> at which time [[Shōzō Makino (theatre manager)|Shōzō Makino]] was the manager of the theater<ref name="new">{{cite book |title=A New History of  Japanese Cinema |last=Standish |first=Isolde |year=2006 |publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group |page=36 |accessdate=September 16, 2012 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZxUv4g_icQC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=Senbonza+theater&source=bl&ots=tGrOMYbmjL&sig=WTsDrMCQqcbP_JSB8G60VYhkeho&hl=en#v=onepage&q=Senbonza%20theater&f=false}}</ref> was directing there.<ref name="Modern">{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of Modern Cinema |last=Abel |first=Richard |year=2005 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |page=703 |accessdate=September 16, 2012 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9cc71Uekc_EC&pg=PA703&lpg=PA703&dq=Senbonza+theater&source=bl&ots=OWUtEqxNBL&sig=SZsGl9EsEPymGM13Jipan6m82uk&hl=en#v=onepage&q=Senbonza%20theater&f=false}}</ref> The [[Yokota Shōkai]] film importation company often screened foreign films at the theater, which had originally been the home of a small touring [[kabuki]] group.<ref name="Modern" />

